<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand-Heroin     08-06 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Heroin,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize Biggest Heroin Refinery In A Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities seized near the Burmese
border what is believed to be the biggest heroin refining complex
uncovered in Thailand in the past decade, a senior police officer
said today.
   About 50 policemen armed with M-16 automatic rifles exchanged
fire with guards before seizing the complex Friday in the jungle
hills of Chiang Dao district of northern province Chiang Mai
province, said Maj. Gen. Kovit Wattana.
   Kovit, commander of the regional border patrol police, said no
policemen were hurt in the gunbattle, after which the 40 to 50
workers in the complex fled into the jungle. No arrests were made.
   Kovit said the complex contained 13 small refineries and six big
stoves for refining opium. He said police seized about 45 pounds of
heroin, 80 pounds of raw opium and 45 pounds of morphine. Opium is
refined into morphine, which is synthesized into heroin.
   Kovit said authorities were trying to track two hill tribesmen
who operated the complex, about 10 miles from the Burmese frontier.
   The area is part of the ``Golden Triangle,'' where the borders
of Thailand, Laos and Burma converge and which is one of the
world's largest producers of illicit narcotics.
</TEXT>
