<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DukakisWorkout 1stLd-Writethru a0564 08-06 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Workout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Takes `Power Walk' While Some Reporters Ride In Limo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS top two grafs to fix spelling of Dukakis</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a week of answering questions about his
health, Michael Dukakis invited _ or perhaps challenged _ the press
corps that travels with him to a spirited speed walk workout
Saturday.
   As the sun rose on Denver at 6 a.m., Dukakis was walking briskly
around City Park, accompanied by a couple dozen reporters, aides,
photographers and network television cameras.
   Also along was California Sen. Alan Cranston, a serious jogger,
and Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, also a jogger.
   Behind, a group of newspaper reporters less committed to
exercise than the Massachusetts governor and Democratic
presidential nominee rode in a dark, stretch limousine, getting out
occasionally to walk a few paces.
   Dukakis regularly spends 30 to 40 minutes in the morning or
evening taking what he calls a ``power walk,'' a fast-paced walk
carrying hand weights in an exercise he says keeps him in shape.
   ``It's enough to get the heart rate up,'' Dukakis said as he
began.
   Normally he works out only with senior aide Nick Mitropolous.
But on his campaign trip Thursday and Friday Dukakis needled
reporters traveling aboard his jet about their health, at one point
calling them an unhealthy looking bunch.
   And at Laguna Beach, Calif., on Friday, he told a large audience
he was inviting the press on his next workout ``as long as they
bring a doctor's letter'' _ remark that hinted at Dukakis' own
doctor's report released Wednesday to squelch unsubstantiated
rumors he had previously sought psychiatric care.
   No letter was required for the workout, however.
   `We're going to get out there and exercise for about 45 minutes
and see just who's in shape and who isn't,'' Dukakis said.
   He and some of those accompanying him walked _ some jogged _
twice around a paved 1.3 mile course through the park and around a
lake. They made the rounds in 35 minutes.
   He ignored the exhaust fumes from gas-powered golf carts that
moved ahead of him, carrying television camera crews and news
photographers, and from the police car that traveled ahead.
   Dukakis also said he didn't feel the effects of Denver's
mile-high altitude. ``It feels pretty good, actually,'' he said.
   Dukakis talked about landscape architecture and public land
acquisition for a while as he walked with Sam Taylor,
concessionaire at the park.
   Dukakis and Mitropolous were the only ones to carry the hand
weights, and Mitropolous readily gave his up to others who wanted
to give the weights a try.
   Dukakis wore blue shorts and a T-shirt given him by the Atlanta
Boys Clubs when he was in that city for the Democratic convention _
and where Dukakis, given a large-sized shirt in a public
presentation, asked that they given him a medium instead.
   ``He said, `If you give me a medium I'll wear it,''' said press
secretary Dayton Duncan, who made the walk. ``They sent him a dozen
mediums.''
</TEXT>
