<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen     08-06 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Counterattacks GOP On National Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential
candidate Lloyd Bentsen counterattacked Republicans on the defense
issue Saturday, accusing them of ``poisoning defense policy with
partisan politics.''
   The Texas senator appeared at a meeting of the American G.I.
Forum, a Hispanic veterans organization, two days after George Bush
told the same group that Michael Dukakis was for ``unilateral
disarmament.'' Bentsen told the group the Republican accusations
missed the mark.
   ``Mike Dukakis supports a strong national defense. I'm strong on
defense. The Democratic party is willing to pay the price to defend
freedom,'' he said.
   ``But,'' he said, ``We won't ever, never wink at corruption in
the Pentagon. And we won't ever, never allow your hard-earned tax
dollars to be used for kick-backs to consultants.''
   The $299.5 billion defense bill vetoed last week by President
Reagan was supported by the Secretary of Defense and the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, Bentsen said.
   When Reagan vetoed it and Bush hailed the action, ``they said
`no' to a strengthened role for the military in stopping drug
traffic. ... They said `no' to a 4.1 percent pay raise for our
service men and women. They said `no' to the biggest defense budget
in history,'' he said.
   ``Unfortunately, They also said `yes' to poisoning defense
policy with partisan politics,'' he said. ``Decisions on national
defense are now being based on the latest political poll at the
White House,'' he said.
   Bentsen received an enthusiastic welcome from the group, but the
400 or so people who listened filled less than half the auditorium.
   Bentsen, himself more conservative than Dukakis on defense and
foreign policy, did not respond specifically to Bush's attacks on
Dukakis' defense positions, including opposition to new nuclear
weapons systems. He also made no mention of the Senate's current
wrangling over aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, which the senator
supports but Dukakis opposes.
   The American G.I. Forum is a 150,000 member organization of
Hispanic veterans formed after World War II, and Bentsen made a
general pitch for support from the Hispanic community.
   ``You will see an administration committed to good jobs at fair
wages _ not just along the East and West coasts, but here in Corpus
Christi, in the Rio Grande Valley ... in the barrios of Los
Angeles,'' he said.
   Hispanics are important in the 1988 election, he said. ``You are
strongest in the states where this election could be decided _ here
in Texas and in California.''
   He poked at Bush's promise to put a Hispanic in his Cabinet.
   ``Hispanic Americans aren't maneuvering for a Cabinet post,'' he
said. ``What they're saying is ... `Don't do us any favors _ just
put is where the action is.'''
   Some in the group had been critical of Dukakis for not
appearing. Bentsen, a native of the Rio Grande valley and a bomber
pilot in World War II who has a long relationship with the group,
tried to deflect that criticism.
   Speaking in Spanish, he said he had asked group president Hector
P. Garcia why the vice presidential candidate was not sufficient.
Garcia told him, he said, ``Oh, Lloyd, you're not important. You're
family.''
   Bentsen received 90 percent of the Hispanic vote in his last
Senate campaign in 1982. In addition to seeking the vice
presidency, Bentsen is on the ballot in Texas for re-election to
the Senate.
   Bentsen's stop in Corpus Christi was part of a one-day campaign
sprint. He was stopping next in Kentucky at a big picnic before
returning to Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880806-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Evangelism     08-06 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Evangelism,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Churches Failing to Reach Out, Losing Hold in America, Leaders Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches are losing their hold on the
hearts and souls of Americans in part because they're too busy
taking care of their own to reach outsiders, leaders at an
evangelism conference said.
   ``We do almost nothing for the truly `unchurched,''' said the
Rev. Alvin A. Illig, director of the Washington, D.C.-based Paulist
National Catholic Evangelization Association.
   He noted that 44 percent of adult Americans _ 78 million people
_ consider themselves ``unchurched,'' meaning they belong to no
church or attend services only on holidays or for weddings or
funerals, according to a recent Gallup poll.
   That is up from 41 percent, or 61 million, 10 years ago, the
Gallup Organization said.
   Ninety-nine percent of U.S. Catholic parishes consciously choose
not to try to reach the average of 4,000 unchurched people who live
in each parish, Illig said Friday at Congress '88, a national
evangelism conference in this Chicago suburb.
   ``The vast majority of our time, effort and money is spent on
maintaining the faith of the active,'' added Illig, whose
organization is a missionary arm of the church that reaches out to
inactive Catholics and non-Catholics.
   Protestant churches are just as guilty as Catholic churches in
that regard, Illig said.
   Paul Benjamin, director of the Washington, D.C.-based National
Church Growth Research Center, agreed.
   ``American churches are going to have to take a really sharp
look at themselves,'' said Benjamin, a minister in the 1.5-million
member Christian Church movement.
   ``There's a tendency in the church to go along with business as
usual. What these people want is a congregation that has warmth and
... a biblical emphasis,'' he said.
   ``I think churches are going to have to tone down their blatant
fundraising and realize that people are more important than
things,'' Benjamin added.
   Sometimes churches are put off by the challenge of reaching
potential members, Illig said.
   ``That's a community of people that is often non-responsive, and
it's an enormous amount of work with very little results, and at
times it can be very discouraging,'' he said.
   But it can make all the difference, said the Rev. William J.
Carl III, pastor at First Presbyterian Church in Dallas.
   In the 1970s, he said, his church made a pivotal decision not to
follow affluent members to the suburbs, and to start caring for the
homeless and hungry on its doorstep.
   ``The press picked it up, and we got a flood of volunteers and
money,'' said Carl, whose 1,850-member church now boasts $1.1
million in annual pledges, almost double the $600,000 low reached
during its transition period.
   ``We have served 800,000 meals in the last 13 years,'' Carl said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880806-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-Text     08-06 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Text,700</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's radio address Saturday, given by Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga:
   Good afternoon.
   America's defense and foreign policy can only be successful when
it is supported by a bipartisan consensus in the Congress. We are
reminded of this truth by the withdrawal of Soviet forces from
Afghanistan and the recent ratification of the Intermediate Nuclear
Forces Treaty.
   These achievements were not merely coincidences. The courageous
Afghan resistance to Soviet invaders was supported by two
presidents and by a strong bipartisan consensus in the Congress.
The important steps leading to the INF Treaty were started by the
Carter administration and pursued with determination by the Reagan
administration, with consistent support from Republicans and
Democrats in Congress.
   On the other hand, disarray in our defense and foreign policy
has usually been the product of a divided Congress and a divided
America, and can often be traced to irresponsible positions taken
during presidential campaigns. Our nation's failure to deploy a
survivable land-based missile, as well as the delays and costly
mistakes made in deploying a new penetrating bomber, and especially
our inconsistent and unsuccessful policy in Central America, are
vivid examples.
   This week, President Reagan's veto of the National Defense
Authorization Bill represents another serious setback to building a
bipartisan consensus regarding America's national security policy.
   Although Vice President Bush clearly was anxious to toss
national defense into the political arena, I had hoped that
President Reagan would place national security above partisan
considerations.
   I had hoped that President Reagan would listen to those who
urged him not to veto this important bill, including his secretary
of defense, his national security adviser, and key Republican
members of Congress who are experts on national defense, like Sen.
John Warner, Sen. Strom Thurmond, Sen. Ted Stevens, Sen. Bill Cohen
and Sen. Jake Garn. Unfortunately the president followed the advice
not of his national security team, but rather of Vice President
Bush's political team. He made this decision without consulting a
single Democrat in the Congress.
   We will continue to work for the enactment of this important
defense bill, but it will not be easy to put Humpty-Dumpty back
together again. Congress must be clearly told who speaks for the
president on national security matters. I am confident that we can
develop a bill that is acceptable to President Reagan's secretary
of defense and his national security adviser, but I do not believe
we can reach agreement with the vice president's political pollster
and his campaign manager.
   The challenge before us, however, is much broader than simply
getting this important bill enacted.
   If we are to safeguard our nation's security, we must insist on
clarity and common sense in our security strategy; tough-minded
management of the Pentagon; measures to reduce the risk of war; a
greater sharing of the burden of defense by our allies; and a
foreign policy grounded in respect for our Constitution and our
basic values.
   The next president must appoint experienced, capable managers
who will insist on getting our money's worth _ every defense dollar
spent. It takes more than a cash register to run an efficient and
effective Pentagon. And it takes more than an adding machine to
formulate a sound strategy and to set realistic priorities.
   In recent years too many tax dollars have been wasted because we
have produced too many procurement scandals and too few effective
weapons.
   We must also call for a new relationship with our allies, to
achieve a more equitable sharing of defense tasks and to improve
our common defense through sensible specialization.
   Finally, we must recognize that America's power rests not on
military might alone, but on a competitive economy; a solvent
government; an educated people; and, above all, on the democratic
principles that we exemplify to the world.
   As the campaign heats up and the political rhetoric inevitably
increases, I hope that we will remember that our national security
is too important to be the hostage of partisan politics. The late
Sen. Scoop Jackson said it best when he said, ``In matters of
national security, the best politics is no politics.''
   Thank you, and have a nice weekend.
</TEXT>
