<HEAD>Plane Overshoots Runway; Twenty Reported Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boeing 747 slid off the end of a
flooded runway while landing Saturday, and officials said three
people were injured. Passengers said up to 20 people were hurt.
   People on the Pakistan Airlines jet said the injuries occurred
when emergency exit chutes didn't reach the runway and passengers
fell to the ground.
   Tariq Saeed, president of the Pakistan Federation of Chambers
and Industry, was on the flight from Islamabad, the capital, to
Karachi, Pakistan's largest city. ``When the aircraft overshot the
runway, we feared the plane might catch fire. There was panic when
the cabin crew asked us to leave the aircraft through the emergency
exits,'' he said.
   Saeed said one passenger suffered fractures when he came flying
out of the short emergency chute and landed on the runway.
   An airline spokesman said heavy rains had flooded parts of the
runway, causing the jumbo jet to hydroplane.
   It wasn't known how many people were on the flight. A Boeing 747
can carry more than 400 people.
</TEXT>
