<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalStrike     08-06 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Strike,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Hospital Nurses, Service Workers Join Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Registered nurses and service workers put
up picket lines Saturday at French Hospital, joining strikes
against seven other hospitals in San Francisco and the surrounding
area.
   Negotiations between the hospital and the California Nurses
Association, representing French's 130 nurses, broke off Thursday
and talks with Local 250 of the Hospital and Health Care Workers
Union broke off Friday.
   Lawyer Laurence Arnold, chief negotiator for French, said the
sides remained far apart on wage issues.
   Meanwhile, talks with nurses at two public hospitals and city
health centers continued into the weekend. Local 790 of the United
Public Employees had granted two extensions, but union negotiator
Jean Smith warned: ``We don't want to give this an infinite amount
of time.''
   `We are talking and we are making some progress,'' said Smith.
   Seven hospitals in the Affiliated Hospitals group were in the
12th day of a strike by 1,700 health-care workers, such as
orderlies, dietitians and licensed vocational nurses.
   The other Affiliated hospitals are Children's, Marshal Hale,
Mount Zion, St. Francis, Pacific Presbyterian and St. Mary's, all
in San Francisco, and Seton Medical Center in Daly City. All except
Pacific Presbyterian were in the fifth day of a strike by 2,000
registered nurses belonging to the CNA.
   Local 250 is locked in a dispute over health benefits and sick
leave and the nurses' union is fighting for higher wages.
   At the seven hospitals affected by the striking Local 250 and
the CNA,
   Outside workers and nurses were flown in to cope with the
walkouts at the Affiliated hospitals. However, the number of
patients dwindled to 772 by Thursday, down from 895 earlier in the
week.
   No new talks have been scheduled among the struck hospitals.
   In anticipation of the strike against French, all admissions but
emergencies were cut off and elective surgeries were canceled, and
by Friday the number of patients had dwindled to about 40, half the
usual number.
   French's nurses are demanding raises of 11 percent and 10
percent over the next two years. The hospital has offered three
raises of 6 percent each over the next 31 months.
   Meanwhile, negotiations continued in an attempt to avert a
strike Thursday by 1,600 nurses belonging to Local 790 against two
public hospitals, San Francisco General Hospital Laguna Honda
Hospital, and city health centers.
   Local 790 originally set a strike deadline for last Monday but
twice extended it after city Health Department Director Dr. David
Werdegar and two deputy mayors entered negotiations Wednesday.
   The public hospitals have been under a wage freeze and nurses
did not get an expected raise this year. The nurses want a two-year
contract with a guaranteed 14 percent raise, and limits on the
number of patients to nurses in critical care sections; the
hospitals want a one-year contract with a continued wage freeze.
   The city has an emergency plan if a strike occurs at General,
which cares for the city's poorest and sickest patients, and Laguna
Honda, which cares for more than 1,000 elderly. The plan includes
seeking help from hospitals in surrounding counties, volunteers and
private ambulance companies.
</TEXT>
