<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Gurkha     08-06 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Gurkha,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gurkhas To End Homeland Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Gurkha separatist
movement formally announced the end of a violent 2-year-old
insurgency Saturday, the United News of India said.
   ``The Gurkhaland movement has ended,'' the news agency quoted
Subash Ghising as saying in Darjeeling in the West Bengal state.
   Gurkhas, who are Indian citizens of Nepalese descent, live
mainly in the tea-growing Darjeeling region in northeastern India.
Ghising's Gurkha National Liberation Front has been seeking a
separate state within the Indian union since April 1986 to protect
the Gurkha's culture and language.
   More than 300 people have died in the Gurkha rebelllion against
the Indian government.
   Ghising made his announcement shortly after returning from New
Delhi, where details were worked out on an agreement reached in
July with the India government.
   Under the agreement, Gurkhas are to receive limited
administrative control of the 1,230 square miles Darjeeling area.
   An estimated 650,000 of India's 2.1 million Gurkhas live in the
Darjeeling district.
</TEXT>
