<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp     08-06 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Wraps Up Western Campaign Swing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis met with Western
governors and other Democratic officials Saturday, declaring he
``loves the West'' and leads in the region over Republican George
Bush.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor and Democratic presidential
nominee, met in private for nearly three hours with the Democratic
group and emerged saying they were in broad agreement on Western
concerns and the chances for a Democratic victory in the region
that has been dominated by the GOP in presidential elections since
1964.
   ``We're ahead now, there's no reason why we shouldn't stay ahead
and build on that lead, and I think it's because the people of the
West are ready for change,'' said Dukakis, who later donned a
cowboy hat and was presented with a pair of cowboy boots.
   ``I think we have an opportunity to win the West, and I mean all
the West,'' he said.
   Dukakis revealed no specific policy agreements reached with the
nearly 50 elected Democrats including governors from 10 states,
members of Congress and former governors. On questions of water and
oil, big issues in much of the West, Dukakis said only that he
wanted a ``national energy policy'' and a ``national water
policy,'' while voicing caution about diverting water between
regions.
   Among those present for the meeting were former presidential
candidates Bruce Babbitt, the former governor of Arizona, and Gary
Hart, the former Colorado senator.
   Dukakis' running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, was
campaigning in his home state Saturday, where he told a group of
Hispanic veterans that the Republicans were playing politics with
national defense.
   ``Decisions on national defense are now being based on the
latest political poll at the White House,'' Bentsen said in an
appearance before the American G.I. Forum.
   Bush, meanwhile, was spending the weekend at his home at
Kennebunkport, Maine, where no public events were scheduled.
   Dukakis was concluding a three-day campaign swing that took him
from Mississippi to California and Washington state before stopping
in Colorado.
   Dukakis began his day in Denver with a brisk, 2.6 mile walking
workout at dawn in a park, along with Colorado Gov. Roy Romer,
California Sen. Alan Cranston and some of the reporters and
photographers who travel with him.
   Dukakis invited them along at the end of a week in which he
faced questions about his health. He later said of the press,
``They're in bad physical condition and I'm worried about them.''
   He spoke to about 2,000 people at an outdoor rally in the same
park, standing in the hot sun before a spectacular view of spouting
water, the Denver skyline and the Rocky Mountains. He planned a
brief stop in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, on his way back to Boston.
   Dukakis enjoys a substantial lead over Bush in most national
polls, but pollsters rate Colorado as a tossup.
   Appearing with some of the officials at a news conference after
the meeting, Dukakis said he favored placing restrictions on small
handguns but said he recognized the ``perfectly legitimate right''
of sportsmen and others to own guns.
   ``My principle concern is small, concealable handguns whose only
purpose is to kill people,'' Dukakis said. He had been asked if he
supported national gun control legislation.
   Referring to those small weapons, he said, ``I think they have
to be subject to strict regulation.''
   Making his second visit to Colorado in a month, Dukakis
described himself as someone who ``loves the West,'' and that after
campaigning in the region he is ``impressed even more with its
grandeur, its uniqueness, with the independence and the values of
its people.''
   ``Believe me,'' he said, ``you're going to see me out here many,
many times'' if elected.
</TEXT>
