<DOCNO> AP880806-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Governors-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0547 08-06 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,690</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new to update with opening news conference,
picks up 7th graf pvs: An early</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican chairman of the National
Governors Association opened the group's election-year meeting
Saturday with a pledge to make the conference non-political and
non-partisan.
   ``I'm going to display tremendous discipline,'' said Gov. John
Sununu of New Hampshire, a strong supporter of Vice President
George Bush and frequent critic of Gov. Michael Dukakis, his
Massachusetts neighbor and the Democratic nominee for president.
   Dukakis planned to attend Tuesday's final session of the
four-day meeting of the nation's governors.
   President Reagan was flying in Monday to address the conference.
   At a news conference opening the meeting, Sununu said, ``I'm
aware that our meeting has been bookended by the two major
political gatherings of 1988 _ the Democratic National Convention
and the Republican National Convention.
   ``We're also as governors very much aware that the success of
the NGA depends on the very bipartisan, non-partisan character of
our deliberations.''
   He added that ``for my part I'm going to try to make this the
most non-political, non-partisan, non-presidential year event that
you've ever seen.''
   Participating in the news conference with Sununu were two
Democratic governors, host Richard Celeste of Ohio and Gerald
Baliles of Virginia, who is slated to succeed Sununu as NGA
chairman.
   The two Democrats agreed that during the past seven and a half
years, President Reagan had succeeded, at times over the protests
of governors, in transferring many domestic responsibilities from
the federal government to the states.
   In keeping with Sununu's admonition to keep the meeting
non-political, neither he nor his Democratic colleagues would
address directly the question of how they felt Bush and Dukakis
would deal with relations between the federal and state governments.
   ``I won't touch that one with a 10-foot poll,'' said Sununu.
   Sununu has had a long, bitter fight with Dukakis over the
Seabrook nuclear power plant. Dukakis played a key role in blocking
licensing of the facility that sits on the New Hampshire seacoast
near the Massachusetts border.
   An early backer of Bush for the GOP presidential nomination,
Sununu was one of three governors said to be on Bush's list of
potential vice presidential choices. The other two were Jim
Thompson of Illinois and Carroll Campbell of South Carolina.
   Gov. George Deukmejian of California sent Bush a letter asking
that he not be consider for the No. 2 spot on the national ticket.
   The Republican National Convention convenes on Aug. 15 with Bush
the certain presidential nominee.
   Another governor, Thomas Kean of New Jersey, will deliver the
convention keynote address.
   Democrats outnumber Republicans among the nation's governors by
a margin of 27 to 23, but many states expected to be major
battlegrounds in the presidential election have Republican
governors.
   In addition to California, Illinois, and New Jersey, they
include Texas with Gov. William Clements and Florida with Gov. Bob
Martinez.
   Big states with Democratic governors include New York with Mario
Cuomo, Pennsylvania with Robert Casey, Ohio with Richard Celeste
and Michigan with James Blanchard.
   Governors who played key roles at the Democratic convention last
month that nominated Dukakis for president and Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen for vice president were Blanchard who was chairman of the
Democratic platform committee and Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas who
delivered the speech placing Dukakis' name in nomination.
   Once thought of as officials who could make a difference
politically in their states, governors have lost some of that
luster in recent presidential elections.
   The fact that Democrats held a majority of the governorships in
1980, did not help Jimmy Carter win re-election against Reagan's
challenge. And, of course, a Democratic majority in statehouses did
nothing to stem the Reagan landslide in 1984.
   The National Governors Association was meeting at a time when
many of the chief executives were expressing concern over what they
consider the erosion of the role of states in their relationship
with the federal government.
   ``Because of Supreme Court decisions in recent months and years,
Congress is free to regulate every minute detail of state
administration and management, and every sector of society that
states traditionally had regulated,'' said Sununu.
   One of the court decisions that upset governors was a ruling
last spring that declared Congress had the authority to end the
federal tax exemption for state and local bonds.
</TEXT>
