<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sub Commission,0131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USS San Juan Joins Fleet in Connecticut Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS San Juan, the Navy's newest
submarine, was commissioned Saturday during a ceremony picketed by
anti-nuclear weapons demonstrators.
   The nuclear attack sub, built by General Dynamics Corp., is the
third U.S. Navy ship to bear the name San Juan, the capital of
Puerto Rico.
   The vessel is 360 feet long, 33 feet wide and displaces about
6,900 tons of water when submerged. A so-called Los Angeles-class
sub, the San Juan is designed to hunt and destroy enemy submarines.
   About 10 anti-nuclear weapons opponents staged a demonstration
outside the submarine base to protest the commissioning. There were
no arrests, police said.
   Puerto Rico territorial Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon attended the
ceremony.
