<DOCNO> AP880806-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Press     08-06 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Press,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize Copies Of Anti-Apartheid Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers across the
country Saturday seized newsstand copies of The Weekly Mail, a
prominent anti-apartheid newspaper.
   Clive Cope, the newspaper's business manager, said the
commissioner of police had ordered the seizure in terms of
state-of-emergency regulations but had not specified a reason for
the action.
   The emergency regulations authorize seizure of publications
which government officials deem to contain subversive statements.
   The Weekly Mail's co-editor, Irwin Manoim, said the newspaper
would file an urgent application in Johannesburg Supreme Court
challenging the seizure and requesting an explanation for the
action.
   The Weekly Mail is published on Fridays, and Cope said most of
the 32,000 copies of the latest edition would have been sold by the
time the seizure was conducted Saturday morning.
   ``We don't have any idea why this happened,'' Cope said. ``We're
quite baffled by it.''
   Established in 1985, The Weekly Mail is oriented primarily
toward white liberals. It is respected for its aggressive reporting
and the generally high caliber of writing.
   The government has warned the newspaper twice in recent months
that it faced a possible three-month suspension for violating
censorship rules.
   Such suspensions were imposed this year on two other
anti-apartheid newspapers, New Nation and South. They have resumed
publication.
   Articles in the current edition of The Weekly Mail include a
report of black municipal policemen fatally shooting a black high
school pupil in Soweto and a package of stories about a group of
143 white men who Wednesday announced their intention to refuse to
perform mandatory military service.
   One section of the emergency regulations defines as a
``subversive statement'' any comment construed as undermining the
conscription system.
   The emergency regulations in effect since 1986 also restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions and treatment of
detainees.
   Under apartheid, South Africa has a racially segregated society
in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs.
The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
