<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Says Nine Dead in Rocket Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas staged a rocket
attack on the eastern Afghan city of Jalalabad, killing nine people
and injuring 10, official Kabul radio reported Saturday.
   The attack occurred Friday, the radio said in a broadcast
monitored in Pakistan.
   Afghan rebels have been fighting the Soviet-backed government
for 10 years.
   The radio also said Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
was still in the Afghan capital of Kabul on Saturday and met with
federal and provincial government officials.
   On Friday, the radio reported Shevardnadze had left the Afghan
capital. The broadcast Saturday made no reference to the earlier
report.
   Shevardnadze made a surprise trip to Kabul on Thursday for
meetings with Afghan President Najib.
   Kabul radio also said Soviet soldiers would be be pulled out of
the besieged city of Kandahar in southern Afghanistan.
   According to a U.N.-brokered accord signed in April, the Soviet
Union must withdraw half of its troops in Afghanistan, estimated at
more than 100,000, by Aug. 15. The remainder must be withdrawn by
Feb. 15.
   Soviet and Afghan officials say 35,000 Soviet troops have left
since the withdrawal began May 15.
   Kabul radio quoted Afghan army leaders in Kandahar as saying
they could defend the city against guerrilla attacks without Soviet
assistance.
</TEXT>
