<HEAD>Four Paintings Damaged at Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservation staff of the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art has begun repairing four paintings that were
damaged last week while on display, an official said.
   Museum spokeswoman Pamela Jenkinson characterized the damage as
minor scratching of the varnish covering the paintings, but would
not say how it occurred or who was thought to have done it.
   ``I don't think I should comment on that right now because we
don't comment on security investigations,'' she said.
   The paintings are ``L'Allegro,'' by 19th century American artist
Thomas Cole; ``Still Life,'' by Carlsen, also a 19th century
American; ``Portrait of Cardinal Roberto Ubaldini,'' by Guido Reni,
a 17th century Italian artist, and ``Capricco Piazzo San Marco,''
by Canaletto, an 18th century Italian artist.
   The artwork belongs to the museum's permanent collection and
each piece was in a different room.
