<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Expulsion     08-06 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Expulsion,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Government Expels Canadian Parish Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The military government expelled a
Canadian priest accused of disturbing Haiti's social and political
order after he refused to reveal the names of his parishioners,
radio stations reported Saturday.
   Rev. Rene Poirier, a Roman Catholic parish priest in the
southern town of Grand Goave, was accused by Haiti's army rulers of
making ``insulting public declarations which are liable to disturb
the social and political order established in the country,'' Radio
Metropole reported Saturday.
   Poirier, 54, allegedly refused a demand by a local police
official in Grand Goave that he submit a list of members of his
congregation who attended one of his recent religious services,
Radio Haiti Inter reported.
   Though it is unclear why the official wanted the names, Poirier
is known to be a member of the radical wing of the Roman Catholic
Church which opposes the military government and calls on the poor
to organize themselves politically. He lived in Haiti for four
years, Radio Metropole said.
   Poirier, whose presence in Haiti was judged ``undesirable'' by
the government communique, was arrested in Grand Goave by soldiers,
transported to Port-au-Prince and placed on board a New York-bound
flight Friday night.
   The soldiers also confiscated several cassettes of religious
sermons in Poirier's rectory.
   ``The expulsion of Father Poirier is a warning directed by the
military government at the Catholic Church that any action in favor
of mobilizing the people for democracy will not be tolerated,''
Franklin Midi, a Haitian sociologist and former Catholic layman,
told The Associated Press Saturday.
   Poirier was expelled the same day Haiti's leader, Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy, was on a tour in the Grand Goave region. On the tour,
Namphy said Haitian problems should be solved by Haitians, not
foreigners.
   Namphy also vowed the army would harshly put down any public
disorder.
   The armed forces chief deposed civilian President Leslie Manigat
in June and sent him into exile. Namphy headed a three-man junta
that ruled Haiti for two years after former President Jean-Claude
Duvalier was ousted in February 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
