<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-06 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Try To Make Their Way East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over wide sections of
the eastern half of the nation Saturday, with some rain also in the
Southwest, and a cold front brought almost autumn-like cool relief
to part of the northern Plains.
   Showers and thunderstorms were widespread ahead of a slowly
moving cold front that curved from New York state into the middle
Mississippi Valley.
   Thunderstorms were scattered over parts of central and eastern
New York state, with heavy rain reported at Albany. Showers and a
few thunderstorms spread from western and central parts of
Pennsylvania into much of Kentucky.
   Rain and thunderstorms also extended off the central Gulf Coast.
Low pressure over southwestern Mississippi brought brief heavy rain
to coastal parts of Louisiana and Mississippi and into the southern
third of Alabama. Those storms also spread west into parts of
southeastern Texas.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered in western North
Carolina through central and eastern South Carolina, southeastern
Georgia and much of Florida.
   A cold front extending from south-central Canada to northern
California also triggered showers and thunderstorms.
   Ahead of the cold front, afternoon temperatures were in the low
to mid-90s, but behind the front, readings were mostly in the low
to middle 60s and Cut Bank, Mont., dipped down to 55 degrees.
   Livingston, Mont., recorded wind gusting to 66 mph early in the
afternoon while the front was crossing the area.
   Widely scattered showers developed across the eastern half of
Arizona and western parts of New Mexico, and showers and
thunderstorms developed in Arkansas and into northeastern Texas and
parts of western Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., and Tacoma, Wash., to 103 at Williston,
N.D.; Gila Bend, Ariz.; and Blythe, Imperial, Palm Springs and
Thermal, Calif. The nation's low Saturday morning was 37 degrees at
Truckee, Calif.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from central and eastern New England through the middle and
southern Atlantic Coast, the central and eastern Gulf Coast and
northern and central Florida. Showers and thunderstorms developing
during the afternoon and evening were forecast from the upper
Mississippi Valley through middle Missouri Valley into parts of the
northern and central high Plains, and over parts of the West.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast and in
parts of northern Idaho and northwestern Montana; in the 80s from
the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah to the Rockies, and from
the central and eastern Great Lakes through the upper Ohio Valley
and central Appalachians to the mid-Atlantic region and New
England; in the upper 90s to around 100 in much of central and
western Kansas, and the central and southern Rio Grande Valley;
between 100 and 110 across the desert Southwest; and in the low to
mid-90s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
