<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Church     08-06 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Church,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Runcie Says ``Impossible'' Conference A Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie, leader of the world's 70 million Anglicans, told the
closing session of the Lambeth Conference of bishops Saturday that
what had been called an ``impossible'' conference was a success.
   The first meeting in 10 years of the Anglican bishops was
overshadowed by the prospect of the consecration of the first
Anglican woman bishop in the next few months by churches in Canada
and New Zealand and the U.S. Episcopal Church. ``Some thought this
conference was impossible. Reason and experience suggested we would
fall apart. But keeping our eyes on the Lord we have not sunk,''
Runcie said.
   Critics said the controversial issue of the first woman bishop
would break up the three-week conference in Canterbury, wrecking
the Anglican Communion of 27 self-governing churches in 164
countries.
   The opponents say the act would irreparably damage the bonds
with Anglican churches that want to keep the all-male episcopate
and the church would decline into a loose federation, with some
dioceses breaking away.
   The critics say traditionalist bishops would feel they could not
be in communion with the consecrated women because bishops are
regarded as successors of the apostles of Jesus Christ, who were
all men.
   But Runcie masterminded a compromise resolution which by a
423-28 vote pledged the churches to respect one another's decisions
and instructed him to set up and head a commission to examine
relations between the churches when a woman bishop is actually
consecrated.
   ``I hope I speak for many others beside myself in testifying
that this conference has for me created spiritual energy and fresh
vision,'' Runcie said.
   After three weeks of debate over issues of poverty, injustice,
militarism and war, the 66-year-old archbishop said of the
conference:
   ``It has not been without conflict, because persons of flesh and
blood inevitably move in and out of conflict and grow through it.
Most of all it has been joyful discovery _ the discovery of a
common treasure despite our diversity.''
   Runcie concluded with a quotation from a sermon preached more
than 30 years ago at Cambridge by Martin Niemoeller, the German
Lutheran pastor and opponent of dictator Adolf Hitler.
   ``As long as the church lives only for herself, as long as Peter
_ the first of the apostles _ does not leave the boat, she lives
safely and undisturbed,'' he said.
   The bishops voted Friday to let England continue appointing
their leader, the archbishop of Canterbury.
   Pressure for an end to the custom stems from the rapid growth of
the Anglican Church in Africa, Asia and the Pacific.
   The bishops voted 177-163 against a resolution asking the
churches to ``consider the implications of the archbishop of
Canterbury being appointed from among any of the bishops of the
Anglican Communion.'' Forty-four delegates abstained.
   Runcie is spiritual head of the Church of England and leader of
Anglicans worldwide, including 2.5 million Episcopalians in the
United States.
   The conference closes Sunday with a service in Canterbury
Cathedral, the Anglican mother church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
