<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FieldMouse     08-06 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Field Mouse,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Ear Force One' Is Grounded, But Small Iowa Towns Still Get A Lift</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN STEFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Ear Force One,'' a balloon likeness of
Mickey Mouse, was grounded by high wind Saturday, but seven small
Iowa towns still got a lift from the celebration of the 60th
birthday of Walt Disney's famous cartoon character.
   An estimated 15,000 people filled this north-central Iowa
community of 1,200 for a parade, fireworks and birthday party that
doubled as a pep rally for Sheffield and six neighboring towns
depressed by the farm crisis of the 1980s and the drought of 1988.
   Children squealed for attention from Mickey Mouse, his
girlfriend, Minnie, and pals Donald Duck and Goofy, and townsfolk
quickly sold out thousands of T-shirts and other souvenirs at the
start of the two-day festival.
   The Rev. Dick Streeter of First United Methodist Church in
Sheffield, said residents hope the celebration will help the area
commit itself to rebuilding its farm-based economy.
   ``We discovered some things a few years ago that weren't
particularly pleasing. The main street was boarding up, and
enrollment in our schools was declining. We realized that the money
was being funneled to the metropolitan areas,'' Streeter said.
   ``It's amazing what Mickey Mouse has done for us,'' he added.
``This is a Disney movie come to life.''
   Disney spokeswoman Mimi Schaff said the company normally
celebrates milestone birthdays of cartoon characters at Disneyland
at Anaheim, Calif., Disneyworld at Orlando, Fla., or in some major
U.S. city.
   But the fair in Sheffield is the first time Disney has taken its
party to a rural area, she said.
   The celebration was part of the unveiling of ``Kernel'' Mickey
Mouse, a huge likeness planted in a 520-acre farm field northeast
of Sheffield, about 90 miles north of Des Moines.
   The field, planted in corn and oats, features a 3{-mile
circumference likeness of Mickey's head and is easily recognizable
from 30,000 feet above the Iowa countryside, although it can't be
seen from the ground.
   The high visibility to 150 commercial airline flights passing
overhead daily is why Disneyland asked farmer Dick Pitzenberger and
his sons to plant the field.
   ``It wasn't that tricky to plant. The curves weren't that
tight,'' said Rick Pitzenberger. ``Cultivating it was a little
tough.''
   Farm fields across much of Iowa are suffering from a severe
drought, and the 6.5 million corn plants that make up Mickey's head
are no different, although they did benefit from some timely rain
earlier this summer.
   Ear Force One, a 12-story hot-air balloon also shaped like
Mickey's head and topped with a birthday hat, couldn't be inflated
because of high wind.
   The communities were putting together a huge birthday card to
give Mickey by the end of the weekend and $7 T-shirts were a hot
item.
   ``We've just been pulling them out of the boxes and selling
them,'' said Mary Schissel of Dougherty, who said the 10,000 shirts
ordered for the two-day celebration were almost sold out in the
first hours of the festival.
   The post office was putting its stamp on the event with a
special cancellation mark for post cards picturing Mickey's
likeness in the field.
   ``We've sold more than 2,000 of them,'' said Jane Etnier, the
Sheffield postmistress, who called the event the biggest thing to
happen in her hometown.
</TEXT>
