<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MoslemLeader     08-06 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moslem Leader,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. and Other Flags Set Aflame at Moslem Leader's Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 wailing mourners at the
funeral of an assassinated Moslem leader beat their chests and
heads Saturday and set fire to U.S., Soviet, and Saudi flags.
   Attackers shot and killed 42-year-old Arif Hussain Hussaini, a
Shiite Moslem leader who headed an opposition political party, on
Friday. The assailants were not identified, and no one claimed
responsibility.
   Party officials said Hussaini was killed outside a mosque in
Peshawar as he left after morning prayers.
   Demonstrators chanted slogans Saturday against President
Mohammad Zia ul-Haq when he arrived at a park where mourners were
gathered. Zia offered prayers for the slain leader.
   Meanwhile, the acting head of Hussaini's opposition political
party, the Movement for Enforcement of Shiite Jurisprudence,
demanded that Saudi Arabia release Iranian prisoners he said were
charged with the 1987 violence in Mecca. About 400 people, mostly
Iranians, were killed in the Mecca unrest.
   If the prisoners are not released by Friday, Sajid Ali Naqvi
said Pakistani Shiites will demonstrate throughout the country.
   Sporadic demonstrations broke out in several Pakistani cities
after Friday's assassination, but they were quickly brought under
control.
   Most Iranians are Shiites, but Sunnis outnumber Shiites in
Pakistan. Both sects hold Mohammad as their prophet, but the
Shiites have been at odds with the predominant Sunni branch of
Islam for 1,300 years.
   Iran observed a day of mourning Saturday for the slain Shiite
leader.
   One mourner, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Hussaini's murder was part of ``America's CIA policy.'' He charged
that United States, Saudi Arabia, Israel and Zia's government were
collaborating to divide Islam.
   Hussaini's party issued a statement Friday calling the
assassination a ``calculated move and a conspiracy to plunge
Pakistan into civil war.''
   A resolution passed by the Punjab branch of Pakistan's leading
opposition party, the Pakistan People's Party, said the killing was
an attempt to thwart opposition demands related to a Nov. 16
general election.
   Zia dismissed the civilian government May 29 and called the
general election in which candidates will be forced to run as
individuals, rather than as members of a political party.
   Opposition parties have called on the president to lift this
condition, saying it is unfair to their candidates. Although
Hussaini also opposed this condition, he was not considered a
radical or an outspoken critic of the Zia.
</TEXT>
