<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NancyReagan 000   08-06 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy Reagan, 000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Joins Chorus Line For PBS Taping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final televised ``In Performance at the
White House'' concert of the Reagan administration was planned to
include a surprise finale _ the first lady Nancy Reagan joining a
kick line from Broadway's ``A Chorus Line.''
   The series ``gives a great deal of pleasure to people who are
watching,'' Mrs. Reagan said in an interview on Saturday afternoon.
``I feel strongly that art is an important part of our lives.''
   She spoke in the library of the White House a few hours before
the last of 17 concerts to be televised during the Reagan
administration, adding that it has been fun for her, too. Since
Marvin Hamlisch has been master of ceremonies, he has had Mrs.
Reagan up and performing several times.
   The final concert _ to be broadcast by PBS on Wednesday _ is the
only one held outside of the White House. A Broadway-size stage,
too big for the East Room, was set up on the South Lawn, for
performances by the Marine Band, an 80-voice choir from Morgan
State University in Baltimore, an alumni cast from ``A Chorus
Line'' and soloists Shirley Jones, Stubby Kaye and Lee Roy Reams.
   ``We've never played one of Marvin's songs before,'' Mrs. Reagan
said. ``Tonight we play `One' and he gets me up to kick with the
chorus.''
   Hamlisch has conferred with Mrs. Reagan about planning before
each of the concerts in the last two seasons. Last season's four
concerts were tributes to American music, to George Gershwin,
Rodgers and Hart, Cole Porter and Jerome Kern. This season's three
concerts salute Broadway.
   Mrs. Reagan thinks the concerts are especially meaningful to
viewers because they're in the White House. Musicians feel it, too,
she says. ``The most seasoned performer becomes very nervous at
performing in the White House. When you go up and feel their hands
and they're ice cold, you do get the idea.''
   ``In Performance at the White House'' began in 1981. Four
concerts by master performers and young talents they'd discovered,
beginning with pianist Rudolf Serkin, born in 1903, and violinist
Ida Levin, born in 1963, were hosted by soprano Beverly Sills.
Country singer Merle Haggard and fiddler Mark O'Connor, 20, were on
that series.
   Concerts were televised from the White House during the Carter
administration but not organized as series with themes.
   The 1982-83 season, hosted by violinist Itzhak Perlman, included
a jazz concert with young singer Diane Schuur, whom Mrs. Reagan
called ``a great, great talent'' and one in which Mary Martin sang
to her. ``It nearly _ it did _ break me up, it was so touching,''
she said. ``I was in a play on Broadway, `Lute Song,' with Mary,''
Mrs. Reagan said. The other two concerts that season were classical.
   Both the Reagans like music, the first lady said, and will
continue as listeners after they retire to Bel Aire, Calif. ``It's
a house we have not lived in before; we sold our house,'' she said.
``It's a little hard getting it ready, 3,000 miles away, but we're
trying to do what we can.''
   They like all kinds of music, she said, adding, ``We're not
crazy about rock.'' She hopes that televised concerts from the
White House will continue with the next administration and said,
``I'll be watching.''
   Only once has she requested a song, Mrs. Reagan said. ``The time
I was in the hospital I asked Barbara Cook to sing `Don't Ever
Leave Me,' a favorite of ours. That's the one show I missed; I saw
it on TV.'' Her health since that October 1987 hospitalization for
a mastectomy has been excellent, she said.
   She has spoken at each televised concert. ``I introduce them and
at the end Ronnie goes up and says a few words and I go up with
him. That has been the usual format.
   ``Marvin has had me sing to Ronnie, `Our Love Is Here To Stay.'
Pearl Bailey sang `Hello, Nancy.' She pulled me up and started to
do a little dance and said, `My feet are so tired.' Then I tried to
do a few steps.'' Some of the audience thought that was planned.
``It wasn't rehearsed,'' Mrs. Reagan said. ``Marvin says he didn't
know that she was going to do this. You know with Pearl, you never
know what she's going to do.''
</TEXT>
