<HEAD>King Hussein Shuts Ministry for Israeli-Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein closed his ministry for
Israeli-occupied territories Saturday, official reports said, but a
government official pledged Jordan would still honor its passports
there and keep the border open to the West Bank.
   Hussein's moves, which included a minor Cabinet reshuffling,
came after his announcement last week that he would sever links
with the West Bank, which Jordan controlled before Israel seized it
in the 1967 Middle East War.
   The decision to transfer the remaining tasks of the Ministry for
Occupied Territories to the Foreign Ministry signaled the king's
view that relations with the territories are now a foreign, not a
domestic matter.
   Hussein has said the changes are in response to the PLO's desire
to ``secede'' and form its own state with its heart in the West
Bank.
   However, a senior government official said Jordan would stay
committed to the ``rights of its fellow Palestinian citizens unless
the PLO asks the contrary.''
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said ``any
citizen who holds the Jordanian passport, wherever he resides and
regardless of his origin, is considered a son of this country.''
   Two-thirds of Jordan's 3.5 million people are Palestinians
carrying Jordanian passports. All West Bank residents and some from
the Gaza Strip hold the Jordanian passport.
   Jordan's decisions unleashed widespread worry among West Bank
Palestinians that they might no longer be allowed to travel to
Jordan.
   Commenting on the possibility of closing down the Jordan River
bridges that lead to the West Bank, the government official said
``this measure will never be taken under any circumstances.''
   The official Jordan News Agency said the king presided over a
Cabinet meeting late Saturday and said the latest moves have
``enhanced the role of the PLO as the prime party in solving the
Palestinian issue.''
   Hussein was quoted as saying that cutting ties with the West
Bank foiled Israeli ``plots'' aimed at setting up Jordan as an
alternative Palestinian homeland.
   The Reagan administration and some officials in Israel have
called for talks on Palestinian autonomy on the West Bank with
Jordanian involvement.
   Jordan's new body for dealing with the occupied territories, the
Palestinian Affairs department, will be under the jurisdiction of
Foreign Minister Taher Masri, the official agency said.
   Under the reshuffling, the incumbent Minister for Occupied
Territories, Marwan Dudin, became minister of labor, state-run
Radio Jordan said.
   A senior Jordanian official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the king was scheduled to leave on a tour to
discuss the policy changes with other Arab leaders. The official
said the king would visit Egypt, Syria, Iraq and a number of
Persian Gulf states in the next few days.
   A move to establish a Palestinian government-in-exile has been
under discussion by PLO leaders, but a senior PLO official in Amman
said his organization ``does not yet have the resources to
achieve'' it.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told The
Associated Press that a high-level PLO delegation would arrive in
Jordan to discuss with Hussein ``the curing of the wounds which
were created by the kingdom's recent measures.''
   The official, who said the delegation would arrive Thursday,
added that the group is worried about ``the political and legal
vaccum left inside the territories.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
