<HEAD>Armenian Dachas to Become Health Care Facilities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian officials are planning to turn country
houses for high-ranking officials into health care facilities for
children and war veterans, Pravda said Saturday.
   ``These former special institutions of rest for high-ranking
officials will be converted into centers to provide follow-up
treatment for children, treatment and rest for the invalids of
World War II and internationalist fighters and for foster
children,'' the Communist Party newspaper said.
   Country houses, called dachas, in the Soviet Union range from
small cabin-like structures to opulent mansions built as summer
homes in czarist Russia. Most used by Communist Party officials as
retreats are large and well-furnished.
   Pravda did not give details on how many country houses are to be
converted or their location.
   Pravda included the report in a story including criticism of
food supplies, transportation and other consumer goods and services
in the southern Soviet republic.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev had criticized mismanagement in
the republic. The criticism came before the republic was torn by
unrest in recent months as Armenians have agitated for annexation
of Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian region of neighboring
Azerbaijan.
   Mass demonstrations and strikes were held in Yerevan, the
Armenian capital, since February, but they quieted down in mid-July
when the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's highest
executive body, rejected the annexation demand.
</TEXT>
