<HEAD>Anti-Nuclear Activists Stage Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs:RETRANSMITTING to eliminate duplicate slug line.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-nuclear weapons protesters displayed
30,000 warhead-shaped cones at the Washington Monument Saturday as
part of national ceremonies marking the dropping of an atomic bomb
on the Japanese city of Hiroshima 43 years ago.
   The cones, about six inches high, were arranged to form a
``ban-the-bomb'' symbol, containing the likeness of a mushroom
cloud. Organizers said the cones _ obtained from a Virginia textile
mill _ were designed to represent a fraction of the 50,000 warheads
stockpiled between the superpowers.
   ``We use all these textile cones to give people an idea of at
least what 30,000 looks like,'' said Pat Jackson, an organizer of
the protest..
   ``Our demonstration today is part of raising the public's
consciousness. I think we get very accepting and just used to all
the nuclear weapons out there. We're here to poke at people,''
Jackson said.
</TEXT>
