<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     08-06 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Pledges End To Discrimination Against Those In 1956
Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarians convicted for their part in
the 1956 popular anti-Soviet uprising will no longer face
discrimination, a high government official pledged in an interview
published Saturday.
   Interior Minister Istvan Horvath also indicated that dissidents
should not necessarily be regarded as enemies of the communist
state, and he predicted reform of the nation's police.
   The minister was quoted by the Communist Party daily
Nepszabadsag as saying that ``the calling to account in court
should not mean an everlasting stigma ....''
   ``The (1956) protagonists ... almost all of them, have now been
discharged from the legal point of view, either as a result of
individual mercy or judicial rehabilitation,'' he was quoted as
saying.
   But he said some cases remain to be settled.
   Horvath's remarks suggested that authorities are willing to end
job discrimination and denial of passports to people who played a
role in the 1956 uprising, which was crushed by Soviets tanks and
troops.
   ``In given sharp social conflicts, at the time of ideological
and political clashes, the term `enemy' may be applicable, but it
may not become a perpetual category. A former enemy could become
neutral, in fact a cooperating partner, even an ally and a
friend,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Horvath also said there should be ``guaranteed sanctions''
against abuse of authority in the name of the state.
   He predicted a reform of Hungarian police but gave no details.
He said public security in Hungary ``excessively carries the
imprint of the approach that had been based on the omnipotency of
the state.''
   Hungarian officials have been liberalizing political policies
along the lines of reforms under Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
They have allowed greater freedom of the press and invited
dissidents to engage the government in a dialogue.
   But they also have said that the supreme authority of the
Communist Party must remain intact.
</TEXT>
