<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay-Church     08-06 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay-Church,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20,000 March Silently in Show of Solidarity with Catholic Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 20,000 people marched
silently through the streets Saturday in a show of solidarity with
the Roman Catholic Church.
   The march, organized by the church, came six days after the
church said it was being persecuted by the government.
   Agents of President Alfredo Stroessner, who has ruled since
seizing power in a 1954 coup, watched the demonstration but did not
intervene. No incidents were reported.
   Tensions between the government and the church have risen since
July 25, when Spanish Jesuit priest Juan Antonio de la Vega was
expelled to neighboring Argentina, allegedly for publicly
advocating the overthrow of the government.
   Church officials denied the charge and said de la Vega, a
65-year-old theology professor, was explaining Liberation Theology,
a movement that advocates political action to achieve social change.
   The church, visited two months ago by Pope John Paul II, has
called on the government to relax authoritarian rule.
   Saturday's procession ended at the cathedral, where the
archbishop of Asuncion, Monsignor Ismael Rolon, celebrated a Mass.
   Later Saturday, Justice Minister Eugenio Jacquet told reporters
that a government that has the support of a strong political party
and the armed forces need not worry about church processions.
   Last Thursday, students at Catholic University _ the nation's
second-largest with an enrollment of 8,000 in the capital and four
branches in provincial cities _ boycotted classes.
   Last Sunday, priests said in messages read from the pulpit that
the church was being persecuted by the government. The message also
denounced ``arbitrary arrests (and) limitations on freedom of
expression.''
   Saturday's marchers carried banners supporting the church. No
anti-government banners were noticed.
   The estimate of 20,000 people marching was made by the Catholic
station Radio Caritas.
   On July 30, the church announced that the annual Te Deum Mass of
thanksgiving, set for Aug. 15, would be canceled because of de la
Vega's expulsion.
   The mass has been canceled on two previous occasions _ November
1969 and May 1972. Both cancellations followed the expulsions of
priests.
   Twenty-one foreign-born priests and religious workers have been
expelled since Gen. Stroessner took power.
   Last February, Stroessner won 86.7 percent of the vote in the
national balloting by which he was re-elected to an eighth, 5-year
term. Opponents charged massive vote-rigging and fraud.
</TEXT>
