<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Deserter     08-06 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Deserter,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Drops Proceedings Against Afghanistan Deserter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military prosecutor's office has dropped
criminal proceedings against a former army private who deserted in
Afghanistan but returned home last month from Canada, Tass said
Saturday.
   Nikolai Golovin, 25, returned to the Soviet Union on July 19
from Canada, where he had lived the past two years, after Soviet
officials announced a general amnesty for those who deserted or
were taken prisoner during the Afghanistan war, the news agency
said.
   After returning to Moscow, Tass reported that Golovin had passed
on word to other deserters living in Canada that he had suffered no
reprisals.
   Golovin was under investigation for stealing a submachine gun
and selling it to an Afghan when he escaped from his unit in June
1982, it said.
   He was captured by Afghan guerrillas who are fighting the
pro-Soviet Afghan government.
   ``We have taken into account all extenuating circumstances,
including Golovin's voluntary return, and decided to stop the
proceedings and exempt him from criminal responsibility,'' Maj.
Gen. V. Provotorov told Tass.
   Provotorov quoted Golovin as telling investigators he suffered
much in captivity and wanted to redeem himself in his country by
working hard.
   Soviet forces intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979 to
support the communist government. In April, the Soviet Union signed
documents in Geneva agreeing to withdraw its about 100,000 troops
over a nine-month period, beginning May 15 and ending next Feb. 15.
The withdrawal began on schedule.
</TEXT>
