<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrintingCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0660 08-06 0125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Printing Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roof Collapses On Kiplinger Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs:RETRANSMITTING to restore AP logo.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HYATTSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-square-foot section of the roof of
the Kiplinger Washington Editors' printing plant collapsed
Saturday, dumping six inches of roof water onto the presses below,
fire officials said. There were no reported injuries.
   Drains on the roof apparently were unable to handle a large
amount of rain that fell during a thunderstorm, said Tony
DeStefano, spokesman for Prince George's County Fire Department.
   The plant is owned by the Kiplinger Washington Editors which
publishes the Kiplinger Letters and Changing Times magazine.
   The water flowing through the 40-by-40 foot roof hole damaged
rolls of paper, ink and printing equipment. Damage estimates were
not immediately available.
</TEXT>
