<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Gartner     08-06 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Gartner,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New NBC News Chief Makes Debut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Gartner, the Iowa newspaper editor
recently named to head NBC News, wasted no time taking on the
competition in a meeting with TV critics Saturday.
   ``One of the nice things about NBC News is that Tom Brokaw is
not Dan Rather,'' Gartner said when he was asked if news anchors
like CBS' Rather and Brokaw, have too much power. Each is managing
editor of his broadcast.
   With a sharp, dry wit, the former editor of the Des Moines
Register who replaced former news division president Lawrence K.
Grossman less than a week ago deflected questions about his plans.
   Gartner admitted he knows little about broadcasting and has to
learn a new vocabulary.
   ``I was in a meeting the other day,'' he said, ``and one of the
executive producers said, `Can I tell you something without
offending you?' And I said, `Even if you offend me you're going to
tell me, so what is it?' And he said, `Say `tape,' not `film.'''
   ``I'm a new boy,'' he said. ``It would be folly to go in and
start tinkering. I watch television news a lot more carefully than
I did two weeks ago, but I don't have an agenda.''
   The seven-figure salaries of network news stars he is supposed
to oversee don't bother him, said Gartner.
   ``I'll tell you what I told a reporter the other day who asked
how much I made. I said, `Less than Tom Brokaw and more than you.'
''
</TEXT>
