<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Times-CBSPoll     08-06 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Times-CBS Poll,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Leads Bush 50-33 in Latest Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strength among middle-class voters helped push
Gov. Michael Dukakis' lead over Vice President George Bush to 17
percentage points, according to a New York Times-CBS News poll
released Saturday.
   Fifty percent of those polled would vote for the Massachusetts
governor if the election were held now, while 33 percent said
they'd vote for Bush.
   A poll in early July, before the Democratic convention, showed
Dukakis with a 47 percent to 39 percent lead.
   In the most recent poll, Dukakis led Bush in all regions but the
South.
   Of the registered voters polled, 56 percent felt the Democrats
would do more for the middle class; 28 percent said the Republicans
would. Eighty-five percent identified themselves as middle-class.
   Those who identified themselves as moderates favored Dukakis 54
percent to 31 percent for Bush. Dukakis was leading among
independents, 49-32. Democrats who voted for President Reagan in
1984 favored Dukakis 58-18.
   Only 27 percent of those polled had a favorable opinion of Bush
and 33 percent had an unfavorable opinion _ the worst such ratio in
his term as vice president. Dukakis was rated favorably by 38
percent and unfavorably by 19 percent.
   The poll of 941 registered voters was conducted Sunday through
Wednesday and reported having a margin of sampling error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
