<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     08-06 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Tells Washington to End ``Dirty War''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Saturday
the best thing the United States can do to promote democracy in
Nicaragua is to end its ``dirty war'' of aiding anti-government
rebels.
   Ortega speech came two days before U.S. Secretary of State
George Shultz's scheduled arrival in the region. Shultz, on a
nine-nation Latin American tour, has tried to rally allies against
the Nicaraguan government.
   In Washington, the U.S. Senate also is working on a new aid plan
for the rebels, known as Contras.
   ``Let them stop their aggression against the Nicaraguan people,
and this will be the best contribution to peace and democracy,''
Ortega said of U.S. support for the rebels.
   Congressional funding of the rebels ran out in February, but
U.S. Senate Democrats have proposed restoring $27 million in
humanitarian aid.
   It would also provide for trade benefits for Nicaragua if peace,
combined with democratic reforms, is achieved.
   But Ortega said if the Reagan administration and U.S. Congress
want to encourage democracy in his country, ``the only thing they
need to do is immediately stop their dirty war against the
Nicaraguan people.''
   Ortega made his comments in a speech in Esteli, about 90 miles
north of Managua.
   He reiterated the willingness of his leftist Sandinista
government to enter direct negotiations with the United States to
normalize relations.
   Last week, Shultz said he supported regional efforts to achieve
peace but that the Sandinistas were insisting on direct talks with
Washington.
   Referring to a Central American peace plan that is marking its
one-year anniversary Sunday, Ortega said the government still held
out hope for a negotiated solution to the 7-year-old civil war, in
which more than 26,000 people have died.
   ``We Central Americans also committed ourselves to promote
dialogue and peaceful solutions to conflicts'' in the region,
Ortega said.
   The peace plan, signed by five Central American presidents,
calls for negotiated settlements to civil wars in Nicaragua, El
Salvador and Guatemala and democratic reforms in the region.
   Peace talks between the Sandinistas and Contras broke down in
June, although a shaky cease-fire was unilaterally extended by the
government until the end of August.
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, author of the peace plan,
criticized the Sandinistas on Friday for failing to comply with its
terms.
   Shultz returns to Central America on Monday to consult on
Nicaragua with U.S. allies. He failed to obtain a condemnation of
the Sandinistas during a meeting last week with the foreign
ministers of Guatemala, El Salvador, Costa Rica and Honduras.
</TEXT>
