<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz     08-06 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Aides Upset by Statement to Shultz</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Saturday that
aides to the foreign minister were worried by his anti-Nicaraguan
statement to U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz.
   The report in Jornal do Brasil came as Shultz arrived in Rio de
Janeiro to spend the weekend relaxing before continuing his 10-day
Latin American tour Monday.
   On Friday in Brazilia, the secretary gained unexpected support
on the U.S. stand toward Nicaragua.
   Foreign Minister Roberto de Abreu Sodre told Shultz that
Nicaragua is ``out of line'' and must ``return to the democratic
path.''
   Sodre said his remarks were personal, but the statement was
still considered unusually strong for Brazil, which traditionally
has advocated non-interference in the internal affairs of other
countries.
   The Rio daily on Saturday said Abreu's statement ``alarmed''
Brazilian Foreign Ministry high officials, even though the minister
said he was speaking for himself and not compromising the country's
position.
   Brazil officially advocates a negotiated solution of the Central
American civil wars and opposes U.S. funding of Nicaraguan rebels.
   Shultz arrived from Brasilia, the modern inland capital about
750 miles southwest from Rio, where he met Friday with President
Jose Sarney and high officials.
   In Rio, he also had lunch with private businessmen Saturday.
Press coverage was not allowed. He planned to spend the weekend
relaxing, playing golf and going for a boat ride on scenic
Guanabara bay.
   Shultz will continue his nine-country tour Monday. He will go to
Bolivia first and then to Costa Rica, Honduras and El Salvador. On
Wednesday, he will attend the inauguration of Ecuador's new
president, Rodrigo Borja.
</TEXT>
