<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ElectricProblems 1stLd-Writethru a0614 08-06 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Electric Problems, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0614,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Power Failure Strikes Manhattan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with power restored. Edits
throughout to delete outdated matter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Extra police patrols roamed upper Manhattan
Saturday after the city's second major power outage in two days
left tens of thousands of people without fans, air conditioners,
lights and elevators for 21 hours.
   Power was restored about 8 p.m. Saturday when workers repaired
three of five damaged feeder cables, said Consolidated Edison
spokeswoman Laurie Hanson.
   ``At this point it looks pretty good. But we can't rule out any
further problems,'' she said. Power was restored at a slightly
reduced voltage level but would not be noticed by most customers,
Ms. Hanson added.
   The blackout affected Harlem and Upper West Side residents from
Columbia University to Washington Heights, along the Hudson River
side of the island, on a muggy day with a high temperature of 89
degrees.
   The cause of the outage was not immediately known, but another
Con Ed spokeswoman, Pat Richardi, said the recent spate of hot
weather may have been a factor.
   No crimes were reported that were related to the power failure,
police Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell said.
   The outage began about 11 p.m. Friday, while Con Ed crews were
still struggling to restore power to a large area of lower
Manhattan, mostly office buildings near the financial district,
that was blacked out earlier in the day. Power was largely restored
Saturday in lower Manhattan, Ms. Richardi said.
   The upper Manhattan outage began with the failure of the fourth
out of 19 feeder cables that provide power to the region, Ms.
Richardi said. Cables had begun failing the day before, but the
electrical grid was able to re-route power until the fourth
failure, she said. A couple hours later, she said, a fifth feeder
cable failed.
   Included in the area of the blackout were Columbia University,
City College, St. Luke's-Roosevelt Medical Center and several large
housing projects. St. Luke's-Roosevelt was forced to rely partly on
an emergency generator, according to an administrator, Ann Baxter.
   Ms. Richardi said up to 5,000 customers were without power, but
noted that large buildings and institutions are sometimes listed as
a single customer, so the number of people affected was many times
greater.
   About 200 utility workers were assigned to the problem, working
in 80 manholes to replace the damaged cables, she said.
   Con Ed recorded its second-highest day of energy usage last
Tuesday, but power use slowly declined through the rest of the
week, Ms. Richardi said. Still, she said, ``the hot weather has to
be a factor.''
   Asked if there was any tie between the outage in lower Manhattan
Friday afternoon and the one in upper Manhattan Friday night, she
replied, ``I honestly don't know. I'm quite frankly speechless and
perplexed.''
</TEXT>
