<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JailEscape 1stLd-Writethru a0601 08-06 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Escape, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0601,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Prisoners Escape from County Jail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES lead and 8th graf, bgng, `The escapees...', with
capture of two escapees.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS LUNAS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five inmates escaped from jail Saturday
by smashing a hole through a concrete ceiling with a 5-pound chunk
of steel, authorities said. Two were later arrested in nearby
Albuquerque.
   ``I don't know how they got it,'' said Valencia County Sheriff
Lawrence Romero. ``If it came in a cake, it had to be a big one.''
   The escape was reported at 8:45 a.m., Romero said.
   ``We have reason to believe they've been out since 2:30 this
morning,'' he said. ``We had three different reports of attempted
auto theft ... We started getting in the reports about 2:30 or 3
this morning.''
   A pickup truck with two rifles and a pistol inside was stolen
from a volunteer firefighter, and authorities believe the escapees
have it.
   Three jailers were on duty when the inmates fled, Romero said.
All five apparently were in one cell at the north end of the county
jail.
   The escapees were identified as Eleno Avila, 24, of Mexico;
Damien Gonzales, 21, of Los Lunas; Tommy Cordova, 19, of
Albuquerque; Cruz Pacheco, 24, of Mexico; and Jesus Campana, 24, of
Mexico. Gonzales and Cordova were arrested without incident as they
walked along a road Saturday afternoon in Albuquerque, about 20
miles north, said Sheriff's Detective Mark Esparsen.
   Avila was being held on charges of aggravated assault with a
motor vehicle, reckless driving and eluding a police officer;
Gonzales was being held on charges of aggravated assault, battery
and criminal damage to property; Cordova was being held on charges
of residential burglary and contributing to the delinquency of a
minor; and Pacheco and Camapana were federal prisoners.
   Romero said he did not have the charges against Pacheco and
Campana.

</TEXT>
