<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Thailand     08-06 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Thailand,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Tells New Thai Leader Of Hopes For Good Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's prime minister, in a note of
congratulations to Thailand's new prime minister, expressed hope
for improved relations between the two feuding nations.
   Vietnam's Do Muoi sent the one-sentence note Friday, a day after
Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan was formally installed in
office. A text was carried in an official Vietnam News Agency
report seen in Bangkok Saturday.
   It said: ``I am confident that in your new and high
responsibility and with efforts and goodwill from both sides, we
will build up the relations of friendship, cooperation, and good
neighborliness between the Socialist Republic of Vietnam and the
Kingdom of Thailand for the interests of the two peoples and for a
friendly, stable and cooperative Southeast Asia.''
   During the Vietnam war, a Thai army division helped support the
U.S.-backed South Vietnam government in its battle against
communist North Vietnam, which won the war in 1975. Thailand backs
guerrillas fighting Vietnamese forces that invaded Cambodia in
December 1978, and Thai and Vietnamese forces frequently clashed
along the Cambodian border until a recent pullback of troops from
the frontier.
   Thailand also has criticized Hanoi for the flow of people
fleeing Vietnam by boat to Thailand.
   Chatichai indicated Thursday that he would ease the tough
position his predecessors had taken on relations with
communist-ruled Indochina.
   ``There will be changes where our neighbors are concerned,'' he
told reporters. ``We want Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia to be our
markets, not our battlefield.''
</TEXT>
