<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 2257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Dominican-Capsize     08-06 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Capsize,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body of Sixth Victim Found After Dominican Boat Capsizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a sixth
victim washed ashore Saturday after a boat carrying illegal aliens
bound for Puerto Rico capsized in a storm, a navy spokesman said.
   Capt. Sigfrido Pared Perez said the body of the drowned young
woman washed up on the eastern shore of the Caribbean nation.
   He said private fishing boats have joined the navy in searching
for about 11 other people who disappeared when the boat capsized
Friday three miles from the town of Haina on the eastern shore.
   Eighteen people have been rescued, and six _ four women and two
men _ are known to have drowned, Pared Perez told The Associated
Press.
   The 25-foot wooden boat was carrying about 35 Dominicans.
   The survivors were under arrest in Santo Domingo. Police said
they could be accused of complicity in homocide if they don't tell
authorities who organized the illegal journey.
</TEXT>
