<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Korea,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Japanese Women's Passports to be Revoked Before Olympics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The passports of six Japanese women will be revoked
before the Olympics in South Korea because they have been linked to
North Korean spies, a government official said Saturday.
   The Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the government had ``due reasons'' to conclude that
the women, in their 30s and 40s, have had contacts with North
Korean agents operating abroad.
   The Foreign Ministry ordered the six to return their passports
by Aug. 31 to prevent them from engaging in activities that would
``conspicuously and directly damage Japan's interest and
security,'' the official said. He did not elaborate.
   Japan's National Police Agency established an anti-terrorism
team in April to ensure that terrorists do not use Japan as a base
to launch attacks on the Olympic Games, scheduled to begin in Seoul
on Sept. 17.
   The ministry official said one of the six, who was living near
Tokyo, agreed to return her passport. The other five were living
abroad at unknown locations.
   Communist North Korea, capitalist South Korea's bitter rival
since the division of the Korean peninsula after World War II, has
demanded that it be allowed to serve as co-host for the Olympic
Games.
   The International Olympic Committee has rejected the North's
demand, saying the Games are awarded to a single city. North Korea
has said it will boycott the Olympics if it is not allowed to be a
co-host, and South Korea fears its rival will use violence to
disrupt the Games.
</TEXT>
