<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Explosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0636 08-06 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Explosion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0636,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Derails, Hits Nearby Diesel Storage Tank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with authorities saying ammonia leak
prompted evacuation to be extended into the night after fire was
controlled, new explanation of different figures on evacuees.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ELSBERRY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve cars of a freight train derailed
Saturday and hit chemical and fuel storage tanks, igniting a
nine-hour fire, releasing hazardous gas and displacing about 600
residents, authorities said.
   Four firefighters suffered minor injuries in the fire, said Troy
Fire Chief Gerald Cherry, a spokesman for the authorities involved.
   A 15-square-block downtown area in this eastern Missouri town
remained evacuated 14 hours after the accident, which occurred
around 6 a.m., he said.
   Several rail cars hit a diesel tank, puncturing it and allowing
diesel fuel to spill, Cherry said. The fuel and several rail cars
carrying lumber products and piping were engulfed in flames.
   Cherry said the fire at the Lincoln County Agricultural Co-op
was dangerously close to 28,000 gallons of diesel, kerosene and
gasoline being stored. He said a bulk fertilizer plant also was
nearby.
   Throughout the evening, highway traffic was routed around the
town of about 1,900 people about 50 miles northwest of St. Louis.
   The fire was brought under control shortly after 3 p.m., but
residents were not expected to be allowed back to their homes until
early Sunday because of anhydrous ammonia gas leaking from a
punctured tank, Cherry said.
   He said authorities hoped to pump the anhydrous ammonia, a
liquid that becomes a gas when it is released into the air, out of
the storage tank and haul it away.
   The gas is not highly flammable but is dangerous to respiratory
systems and can cause severe burns, Cherry said, explaining why
authorities evacuated at least 200 residents and kept a total of
about 600 from returning to their homes.
   He said the tank that was punctured had a 20,000-gallon
capacity, but contained only between 4,000 and 6,000 gallons of
anhydrous ammonia. Coincidentally, he said, the railroad car that
punctured the tank was also carrying anhydrous ammonia.
   That car was not damaged, but was to be the last of the derailed
cars to be righted, he said.
   The 113-car train had been southbound from Galesburg, Ill., to
St. Louis, said Burlington Northern Railroad spokesman Brian
Sweeney.
   Cherry said about 150 firefighters, including some from as far
away as St. Louis, helped fight the fire with foam and water after
letting it burn itself down for several hours.
   A clean-up crew and investigators were on the scene, Sweeney
said. The cause of the derailment had not been determined.
   The evacuees were taken to a church and a school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
