<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrunkenWitness     08-06 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drunken Witness,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Acquitted On Rape Charge After Witness Testifies While Drunk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with rape was acquitted after
his accuser testified while intoxicated, and a prosecutor said he
wants to review the case to see if the judge acted properly.
   Attorneys said Circuit Judge J.C. Norton refused to look at the
results of a blood-alcohol test given to the alleged victim before
she testified.
   The judge later said he was shocked any lawyer would allow an
intoxicated witness to testify.
   Reached at home Saturday night, Norton declined to discuss the
case. ``I don't think it would be appropriate to comment on it,''
he said.
   District Attorney Roy Johnson said he has ordered a transcript
to review what Norton said to the jury hearing the case against
Henry Gray.
   ``The woman's drinking had been brought to the court's attention
before trial,'' said Johnson. ``If (Norton) did anything improper,
we will take whatever action is necessary.''
   Gray was found innocent Thursday, a day after the woman
testified.
   A defense attorney smelled alcohol on the woman's breath and
requested a test to determine whether she had been drinking. The
test showed her to have a blood-alcohol content of 0.16 percent,
while the legal presumption of intoxication in Alabama is a reading
of 0.10 percent.
   Defense attorney Collins Pettaway said Norton told prosecutors
before the trial he did not want to see any test results ``until
they were properly presented.''
   After the verdict of innocent was read, Pettaway said Norton
told jurors he might have overruled a guilty verdict because of
information about the woman's drinking.
</TEXT>
