<HEAD>Civil Rights Groups March to Protest Acquittals of Three Lawmen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS number of marchers to 400 sted 500 in lead to
reflect later, more reliable estimate, and SUBS 5th graf `Members
from...' with one graf to add Arkansas and update with no arrests
or incidents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HEMPHILL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 people Saturday marched and
held a prayer vigil to protest the acquittal of three white lawmen
in the beating death of a black man jailed on drunken driving
charges.
   The lawmen had been charged with violating the civil rights of
Loyal Garner Jr., whose Dec. 27 death sparked charges of racism in
this East Texas town.
   Those who converged on Hemphill Saturday staged a march to the
Sabine County courthouse, where several people gave speeches
blasting what they called a lack of justice in Garner's death.
   ``I want the men that did it to be convicted, found guilty as
they should be,'' Garner's widow, Corrine, said.
   Members from various NAACP groups in Texas, Arkansas and
Louisiana planned the march and demonstration. There were no
arrests or incidents related to the march, Sabine County sheriff's
officials said.
   Vollie Grace, president of the local National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People, said demonstrators also joined
in a prayer vigil.
   Acquitted last month were Hemphill Police Chief Thomas Ladner,
41, and Sabine County sheriff's deputies James ``Bo'' Hyden, 35,
and Bill Horton, 58.
   Garner, 34, who was arrested Christmas Day for suspicion of
drunken driving, died of head injuries.
   The three lawmen still face murder charges.
</TEXT>
