<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq 4thLd-Writethru   08-06 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0663,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Statement A Breakthrough For U.N. Talks, Cease-fire Expected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for 5th pvs, The U.N. ... to UPDATE with
Iranian official reinterating Iranian support for talks after
cease-fire. Pickup 7th pvs, I think ... </NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Iraq's announcement Saturday that it will accept a conditional
cease-fire with Iran is ``a very important step forward'' for
stalled U.N. peace efforts, and he hoped to declare a truce early
this week.
   ``I received information from the foreign minister of Iraq that
his president has decided to accept an immediate cease-fire
followed by direct talks under my auspices,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   ``I think this is a very important step forward,'' said Perez de
Cuellar. ``The impression I have is that it can solve the problem.''
   But Iran gave no official reaction on President Saddam Hussein's
call to accept a cease-fire if Iran agrees to immediate direct
talks.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati met the U.N. chief
for more than an hour and was presented the Iraqi proposal. Later,
he brushed past reporters without comment.
   In a Saturday night interview with Cable News Network, Javad
Zarif, counselor to Iran's U.N. Mission, reinterated Iran's stand
``to engage in direct talks immediately following a cease-fire ...
within the appropriate framework of the U.N. plan.'' Zarif did not
elaborate.
   Perez de Cuellar said he would meet Velayati Sunday to receive
Iran's formal response to the Iraqi proposal.
   ``I think we are on the way to a final solution of the problem,
with the full implementation of Resolution 598,'' he said after
talks with Velayati. The U.N. resolution calls for an immediate
cease-fire, then a troop withdrawal to international borders and a
prisoner exchange.
   Iraq's U.N. ambassador, Ismat Kittani, met the secretary-general
first to brief him on Hussein's proposal.
   After the meeting, Kittani said: ``If they (the Iranians) accept
this, we are on the road to peace. If they refuse it, then it will
be obvious to everyone that Iran and Iran alone is responsible for
shedding any additional blood.''
   Hussein's dropping of his demand for direct talks before a
cease-fire represented acceptance of Perez de Cuellar's compromise
plan to break the deadlock, according to diplomats who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Peres de Cuellar said Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz was
summoned home Saturday for consultations but would return ``as soon
as I tell him I am ready to initiate the direct talks.''
   ``I hope that I will be in a position'' early this week to
announce the beginning of a cease-fire to end the 8-year-old
Persian Gulf war and other elements of a U.N. peace plan, he said.
   One Middle Eastern diplomat familiar with the talks, speaking by
telephone, said the Iraqi announcement should give fresh impetus to
U.N. peace efforts.
   He described Hussein's announcement as high drama and artful
diplomacy and said he effectively ``tossed the ball back into
Iran's court.''
   Perez de Cuellar told the Security Council Friday he planned to
dispatch a 250-man U.N. observer team to monitor a cease-fire and
troop withdrawal.
   Middle East diplomats said they expected Iran to welcome the
Iraqi announcement.
   The Iraqi president announced Iraq would observe a cease-fire on
condition that Iran agree to enter into direct talks immediately
after a cease-fire.
   Hussein also said Iran must accept implementation of all aspects
of U.N. Resolution 598.
   Iraq accepted the resolution a year ago. Iran, after a series of
battlefield losses, accepted the resolution in a surprise
announcement last month.
   Iraq had demanded face-to-face talks before a cease-fire as a
way of testing Iran's sincerity following its surprise turnaround.
   Iran rejected the demand, but said such negotiations could be
held ``at an acceptable level'' after a cease-fire, troop
withdrawal and prisoner exchange.
   The secretary-general, attempting to break the stalemate,
proposed that both sides announce they accept both a cease-fire and
direct talks. Then he would announce a cease-fire date and
simultaneously call for early direct talks, according to diplomatic
sources close to the talks.
   Details of the secretary-general's plan have not been disclosed.
   The five permanent members of the Security Council are also
working on a plan to guarantee Iraq that Iran will fully implement
all aspects of a truce. The five are the United States, Britain,
China, France and the Soviet Union.
   U.N. diplomats have said that the combination of the
secretary-general's plan and Security Council guarantees should
remove Iraq's inhibitions about a U.N. peace agreement.
</TEXT>
