<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Debt     08-06 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Debt,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third World Countries Discuss Financial Difficulties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Miguel de la Madrid said Friday the
difficult economic prospects facing Third World countries affect
the stability of all nations.
   He spoke at the opening session of a meeting of the Commission
of the South.
   Attending the commission meeting are 28 delegations from
developing countries. After the opening session the representatives
moved to the mountain resort of Cocoyoc for private meetings on
their nations' economic and political problems. The conference will
end Monday.
   De la Madrid said the economic problem for developing countries
``is complicated even more by the onerous service of the foreign
debt and the resistance to solutions that might imply recognition
of coresponsibility and restore the right to development.''
   ``The majority of debtors have managed to avoid confrontations
and unilateral decisions,'' he said.
   Among those attending the conference are former President Julius
K. Nyerere of Tanzania, the commission chairman; former President
Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela and the Cuban vice president,
Carlos Rafael Rodriguez.
   Nyerere, in his opening statement, proposed the debtor nations
organize a forum in which they ``could make more precise ... their
common problems.''
   ``The creditors are strongly organized to defend their
interests,'' he said. ``The debtors aren't organized. Each one
doesn't even appreciate the nature or the magnitude of the problems
of the others.
   ``Because of that, the commission proposes the creation of a
debtors' forum.''
   He also said the commission ``will have to make inevitably a
call for cooperation from the North _ the North that today
dominates as much in economics as it does in politics.''
   The Commission of the South was formed last year in Geneva. It
met in March in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, and this is its third
meeting.
   Its declared purpose is to strengthen cooperation among
developing countries and develop the North-South dialogue.
</TEXT>
