<HEAD>Industrialist and Grandson Believed Abducted, Countess Spared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARDORE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vacationing Italian industrialist and his
15-year-old grandson were missing Friday and feared kidnapped in
southern Calabria after their car was found abandoned near the
Ionian coast, police reported.
   The presumed abduction of Alberto Minervini, 58, and his
grandson of that name occurred two days after the release in the
same area of an 8-year-old boy, Marco Fiora, who was held for 17
months by a kidnap gang.
   Police also reported Friday that a leading society figure,
Countess Marta Marzotto, appeared to have been the intended victim
of a kidnapping by six armed and masked bandits who burst into her
vacation villa at Porto Rotondo, Sardinia, on Thursday night.
   Finding the countess was out, the bandits tied up her mother and
two maids and fled, police said.
   Minervini owns a ceramic factory in Portici, near Naples.
   He and his grandson were driving in a tiny Fiat 500 Thursday
night, family members told police. The car was found pulled to the
side of a road with lights on and motor running.
   More than 200 policemen aided by tracker dogs and helicopter
surveillance searched for the two in the rugged countryside and
mountains but found no trace, police said. The car was found six
miles from the spot where Marco Fiora was released.
   Police said Thursday they arrested eight people in that
abduction, which they believe was carried out by the 'Ndrangheta,
the Calabrian version of the Mafia.
   The kidnappers demanded a ransom of 5 billion lire (about $4
million) but the family paid only an initial installment of 285
million lire ($220,000), police said.
</TEXT>
