<HEAD>Argentine Cost of Living Up 25.6 Percent in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of living increased by
25.6 percent last month in Argentina, placing the inflation rate
for the first seven months of 1988 at 177.9 percent, the National
Institute of Statistics reported Friday.
   Two days ago the government of President Raul Alfonsin adopted
an austerity program with budget cuts, price controls and an 11.4
percent devaluation of the austral, the national currency.
   The austral was introduced in June 1985 to replace the peso. At
that time the austral was worth $1.24 compared to about 7 cents now.
   Inflation for the 12-month period that ended July 31 was 381.2
percent, according to the national institute.
