<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Fabio,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fabio Downgraded, No Longer Threatens Hawaii</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Fabio kicked up some high waves before
it was downgraded to tropical storm status and veered away from the
Hawaiian Islands, the National Weather Service said Friday.
   The weakening storm system was 312 miles south of Hawaii Island
on Friday morning, bringing a chance of rain and cloudiness to the
southern tip of the Hawaiian chain, forecaster Clarence Lee said.
   ``The center is so far away, I don't think it will have any
significant impact,'' Lee said.
   The weather service canceled a tropical storm watch for Hawaii
Island on Thursday and canceled a high surf advisory Friday.
   On Friday morning, Fabio had maximum sustained winds of 46 mph,
which the weather service said classified it as a tropical storm. A
storm must sustain winds of 74 mph or more to remain a hurricane.
