<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Channel Swimmer,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nebraska Man Swims English Channel for Charity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nebraska accountant swam across the 21-mile
English Channel Friday to raise money for children with
life-threatening illnesses, the Channel Swimming Association said.
   Kris Rutford, of Lincoln, Neb., entered the water at Shakespeare
Beach at the southeastern English port of Dover early Friday
morning, the association said. He arrived in France 10 hours and 44
minutes later.
   An association representative, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said she believed Rutford arrived at Sandgatte, France.
However, she said she would not know positively until a group
observer returned Saturday.
   Rutford, who belonged to the University of Nebraska-Lincoln swim
team before graduating in 1981, was trying to raise money for the
Make-A-Wish Foundation of Nebraska. The organization grants wishes
to seriously ill children.
   The fastest Channel swim ever was made July 29, 1978, by Penny
Lee Dean of California. She swam from Dover to Cap Gris Nez,
France, in 7 hours, 40 minutes.
