<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 0649EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Bar     08-06 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Bar,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Don't Make Meese Mistake Again, ABA Chief Tells Dukakis and Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the American Bar Association,
reacting to the troubles of former Attorney General Edwin Meese,
urged U.S. presidential hopefuls Friday to select an attorney
general with the care they would give a Supreme Court nominee.
   Association President Robert MacCrate said in identical letters
to Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis that too
often in the past, presidents have selected ``political friends''
to head the Justice Department.
   ``The care and importance given to the selection of justices of
the Supreme Court should be given as well to the selection of
attorney general,'' he said.
   Addressing a news conference in Toronto, where the bar
association is holding its annual meeting, MacCrate said his
message was prompted by the events of the past 18 months,
culminating in Meese's resignation under a cloud. Meese, a friend
of Reagan, was the subject of a 14-month ethics investigation by an
independent counsel, James McKay. McKay decided against filing
charges but said Meese probably violated conflict-of-interest laws
and willfully filed a false tax return.
   The Reagan administration has nominated former Gov. Richard
Thornburgh of Pennsylvania to replace Meese until the end of the
term.
   MacCrate said Meese was one of many top law officers appointed
through personal connections. He cited Robert Kennedy, attorney
general for his brother John F. Kennedy.
   ``A close connection between partisan politics and the office of
attorney general inevitably reduces the effectiveness of the
department, incites fear about the integrity of the administration
of justice and undermines public confidence in the rule of law,''
said MacCrate, a New York attorney.
   MacCrate acknowledged that the attorney general is in many ways
``the president's lawyer,'' and it's natural that he would choose a
trusted friend.
   He also said the 346,000-member ABA could do more to help ensure
the candidate is qualified.
   Although an ABA standing committee scrutinizes all candidates
for the federal courts, it does not review nominees for attorney
general or other Cabinet posts. ``We should have a machinery to do
it,'' he said.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar will address the
opening assembly of the weeklong annual meeting on Monday. Other
speakers will include CIA Director William H. Webster and former
Supreme Court Justice Lewis F. Powell. About 12,000 U.S. and
Canadian lawyers are expected to attend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
