<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 0652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Mafia     08-06 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Mafia,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Names Commissioner To Head Anti-Mafia Forces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday named a leading terrorism
investigator to head its battle against the Mafia and proposed an
expansion of judicial forces to operate in major centers of
organized crime.
   Domenico Sica's appointment as high commissioner came after a
team of anti-Mafia investigating magistrates in Sicily announced
their resignations last week, saying their work was being
obstructed.
   Several judges involved with the magistrates' team also accused
the government of letting the anti-Mafia effort disintegrate
following the conviction of 338 people in a trial of
organized-crime leaders last December.
   Sica, 56, has investigated many of Italy's major terrorism cases
over the past decade including the kidnap-murder of former Premier
Aldo Moro in 1978 and the shooting and wounding of Pope John Paul
II in 1981.
   Sica replaced Pietro Verga ,who retired.
   ``There isn't much difference between terrorism and the Mafia
and therefore ... I approach my new job with calm and integrity,''
Sica told reporters.
   At Friday's Cabinet meeting, Interior Minister Antonio Gava
proposed the government either create a new intelligence agency to
aid in fighting organized crime or increase the powers of the high
commissioner, Sica.
   Gava also proposed reorganizing the detective force in the
Sicilian capital of Palermo; establishing judicial investigation
squads linked to police stations in Palermo; increasing the powers
of internal revenue agents and creating a special crime-fighting
center in Catania, Sicily.
   The proposals are to be presented to parliamentary commissions.
   Criticism of the government's actions against organized crime
has increased since mid-July when a prominent Sicilian prosecutor,
Paolo Borsellino, said probes by the ``anti-Mafia pool'' of
investigating magistrates in Palermo were being obstructed.
   President Francesco Cossiga called on the interior and justice
ministries and the Superior Council of Magistrates, which oversees
Italian judges, to investigate.
   As the council began hearings last week Giovanni Falcone, the
most famed member of the ``anti-Mafia pool,'' submitted his
resignation and asked for a transfer. The other members of the
group then announced their resignations.
   Falcone said a new chief investigating magistrate, Antonino
Meli, had dispersed the pool and detectives were not cooperating
with the magistrates. But the Council of Magistrates backed Meli.
   ``When men like Falcone and Borsellino talk about leaving their
posts there is a sensation of fear and loss,'' Palermo Mayor
Leoluca Orlando told a news conference this week. He said the post
of high commissioner had turned into a bureaucratic job.
   Sica gained fame for tracking down and prosecuting leftist Red
Brigades terrorists, including those who killed Moro.
   He also investigated Propaganda Due, the right-wing organization
accused of trying to overthrow the government in the early 1980s.
   In Italy's legal system some judges adjudicate court cases, some
are public prosecutors and others investigate crimes with the aid
of police units.
</TEXT>
