<HEAD>Jet Fighter Pilot Killed in Training Mission in Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILLSBORO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet fighter crashed into a southern
Ohio forest during training exercises Friday, killing an Ohio Air
National Guard pilot, authorities said.
   The plane, an A-7D Corsair II attack fighter, crashed and burned
in Pike State Forest, about 15 miles south of Hillsboro, officials
said.
   The pilot was 2nd Lt. Bryan R. Miner, 28, of Reynoldsburg near
Columbus, said Lt. Jim Boling, a spokesman for Rickenbacker Air
National Guard Base in Columbus.
   Miner's plane was one of three planes that took off from
Rickenbacker Friday morning, Boling said. The fighters were in an
air combat tactics training session in a restricted military area
about 70 miles south of Columbus when the crash occurred.
   Boling said a team of Air Force officers will investigate the
crash.
   Robert Ross, whose home is less than a mile from the crash site,
said he went into the area and saw debris all over a hill and saw a
crater more than six feet deep caused by the crash.
   ``There are pieces scattered all over that place,'' Ross said.
</TEXT>
