<DATELINE>BRISBANE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher left Australia on Saturday after a visit marked by
protests of Irish Republican Army sympathizers and homosexual
rights activists.
   Mrs. Thatcher was the first British leader to make an official
visit to Australia in 30 years. She traveled widely on her six-day
tour and held discussions with Prime Minister Bob Hawke.
   On her trip, Mrs. Thatcher warned Australians not to support the
IRA, which is fighting to force the British from the province of
Northern Ireland.
   Six pro-IRA demonstrators held a meeting outside Mrs. Thatcher's
Brisbane hotel Saturday before she left. Police reported no
violence or arrests.
   On Friday, the Conservative leader was greeted in Brisbane by
about 30 protesters from the Australian Aid for Ireland group.
Homosexual rights activists also brandished banners.
   Mrs. Thatcher was scheduled to visit Malaysia and Thailand
before returning to Britain.
