<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Cocaine     08-06 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Cocaine,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says More Tests Needed for Anti-Cocaine Herbicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. anti-narcotics official said Friday a
herbicide is the best way to destroy the coca crop and control
cocaine trafficking, but the chemical needs more testing before it
can be used.
   Ann Wrobleski, assistant secretary of state for international
narcotics matters, said Peru's government will decide whether to
use the herbicide following studies now underway in the eastern
jungle.
   President Alan Garcia on Thursday questioned the safety to
humans and plants of the chemical tebuthiuron, commercially sold as
Spike. He called for more extensive testing.
   U.S. and Peruvian governments are experimenting with the
herbicide on a one-acre test plot near Tingo Maria, 230 miles
northeast of Lima. About 60 percent of the world's coca, the raw
material of cocaine, is grown in the region.
   Anti-drug officials say manual eradication of coca plants and
programs to encourage peasants to substitute other crops for the
lucrative coca leaves have not been effective.
   ``The use of a safe and effective herbicide is the best way to
get a grip on the drug problem,'' Ms. Wrobleski said during a news
conference. She is touring five South American nations and will
meet with Secretary of State George P. Shultz Monday in Bolivia.
   The herbicide's manufacturer, Eli Lilly & Co. of Indianapolis,
has refused to sell the product for use against coca plants in
Peru, citing ``policy and practical considerations.''
   The herbicide is used in the United States but some Peruvian and
foreign environmentalists have said it would damage the jungle
region's ecological system.
   Most of the coca leaves grown in Peru are processed into cocaine
base and then flown from clandestine airstrips to Colombia, where
the base is refined into cocaine for sale in U.S. and European
markets.
</TEXT>
