<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rebounded from a four-day
slump amid reports of a possible resolution to the longstanding
Persian Gulf war.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude, rose 23 cents a 42-gallon barrel Friday to close at $15.26.
   Refined oil products also gained ground. The September contract
for wholesale heating oil climbed 0.58 cent a gallon to finish at
43.04 cents. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for September increased
0.28 cent a gallon to 45.23 cents.
   Energy prices had declined throughout the week, in part, because
OPEC's pricing committee failed to take any concrete action after
meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland.
   But analysts said technical factors and news the United Nations
was persisting in its efforts to bring about an end to the fighting
between oil-producing Iran and Iraq contributed to Friday's
recovery.
   ``Prices rose early because of the potential for a cease-fire,''
said Andrew Lebow, an oil analyst for E.D.&F. Man International
Futures Inc.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced Thursday
that he had received a report from a U.N. military team that
visited both nations about arrangements for a U.N.-supervised
cease-fire. He said both sides are interested in peace talks.
   The U.N. chief was to meet with the Security Council on Friday
about the report, but would not disclose the contents of the talks.
   A truce in the region could signal higher oil prices if the
13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, which
includes Iran and Iraq, can agree on production limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
