<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Knudsen-Agee     08-06 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Knudsen-Agee,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agee Is Back _ at Apogee of Morrison Knudsen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto NY35 of Aug. 5</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Agee is returning from corporate exile to head the
big engineering and construction firm Morrison Knudsen Corp. in his
hometown of Boise, Idaho, six years after his ill-fated tenure at
Bendix Corp. crashed to a close.
   The 50-year-old Agee, who led Bendix in a disastrous attempt to
acquire Martin Marietta Corp., was named chairman and chief
executive officer of Morrison Knudsen on Friday, effective
immediately. He has served on the company's board for a total of 11
years.
   His first order of business will be to return the company to
profitability. Morrison Knudsen's earnings have declined from their
1984 peak. The company posted a loss for the first six months of
1988 of $46.7 million, mainly from the divestiture of its real
estate development segment and poor performance in its
ship-building operation.
   Revenue for the first two quarters totaled $948.8 million.
   ``People don't like to see red numbers,'' Agee said at a news
conference in Boise. ``I like to under-promise and over-perform.''
   A complex man described as both warm and quick on the trigger,
Agee enjoyed an enviable rise up the corporate ladder only to
stumble in the tangled fight for Martin Marietta and rumors of a
sexual relationship with another executive.
   Agee entered the business world at Boise Cascade Corp. in 1963,
a graduate of Harvard's prestigious business school. He joined
Bendix's management team in 1971 and took over as chairman and
chief executive officer in 1977.
   In his five years in the executive suite, Agee shifted Bendix's
emphasis from auto parts to electronics and aerospace systems and
boosted annual sales toward the $5 billion mark. His compensation
of about $1 million a year in salary _ with stock options and
deferred pay to match _ helped make him an object of keen interest
in business circles.
   But Agee's alienation of both colleagues and observers began
when he hired and rapidly promoted Mary Cunningham, an MBA holder
from his alma mater. Rumors of a romantic liaison with her boss
forced Cunningham to resign from the vice presidency of stragegic
planning a year later in 1980, although both continue to deny they
had a relationship while she worked at Bendix.
   Together, however, the two had conceived of an aggressive
acquisition stragegy that would culminate in Bendix's dramatic
fight with Martin Marietta in 1982.
   Rather than embrace Agee's buyout offer, Martin Marietta fought
back ferociously. In a textbook example of the risky and expensive
``Pac-Man'' strategy, Martin Marietta responded by snapping up
shares of Bendix in a counter takeover bid.
   Both companies spent millions of dollars buying stakes in each
other without one completing the acquisition before the other.
Ultimately Bendix was acquired by Allied Corp., which is now
Allied-Signal Inc., for nearly $2 billion in early 1983. Martin
Marietta, meanwhile, was left heavily in debt, and a big portion of
its stock also was acquired by Allied-Signal.
   Agee resigned from a short-lived career at Allied to form a
small venture capital and consulting firm in Massachusetts with
Cunningham, whom he had married in 1982.
   At Morrison Knudsen, Agee is taking the reigns from William
Deasy, 51, who will continue as president. Deasy also will return
to the job of chief operating officer, a position he held before
being elevated to chief executive officer.
   ``Morrison Knudsen is a world class company with world class
growth potential,'' he said in a statement. ``My job is to ensure
that we maintain the financial muscle and clear strategic thinking
to realize that potential.''
   Wall Street appeared to sanction the appointment. Morrison
Knudsen stock rose $1.50 a share to close at $43.50 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Cunningham has been running the privately financed Nurturing
Network, which helps middle-class women who are pregnant and
single. The network has expanded to all 50 states, and she likely
will continue her work in Boise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
